<H3> <TI>   Omsk Import-Export Figures Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  944F0334B Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 9 Feb 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> 944F0334B </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Omsk Oblast Increases Export of </F>
Goods"] 
  [Text] According to the data of the Omsk Oblast 
Administration of Statistics, the oblast exported $335.4 million 
worth of goods in 1993, a 75.8 percent increase as compared with 
1992. Specifically, export deliveries of the petrochemical 
complex comprised 83.1 percent of the overall volume of export 
(1.8 million tonnes). This included 15,600 tonnes of phthalic 
anhydride (base for dyes) and 20,600 tonnes of synthetic rubber. 
Timber materials were exported in the amount of 6,400 cubic 
meters. While in 1992 barter deals accounted for 30 percent of 
the export, in 1993 they accounted for 20 percent. The relative 
share of export deliveries in the overall volume of goods 
produced comprised 9.9 percent, while in 1992 it was 6.8 
percent. Around 80 percent of the export deliveries were made 
under contracts concluded by the enterprises of Omsk Oblast 
directly with the foreign partners. The developing countries 
accounted for 53 percent of the export deliveries, while the 
industrially developed countries, and primarily Germany, 
accounted for around 30 percent. Import comprised $115 million. 
Great Britain (20 percent) and Germany (14 percent) were among 
the primary suppliers. A large part of the import was comprised 
of sugar (19 percent of the overall volume of import) and 
equipment (17 percent). 

</TEXT>

